me>Vanhala</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG020345%2F1"><gtr:id>998EEA9C-1250-4F7B-A380-8A3F6A82D85E</gtr:id><gtr:title>Making Rights a Reality? Disability rights activists and the use of litigation strategies in Canada and the UK</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G020345/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>This project solves the puzzle of variation in participation before the courts by disability advocacy organisations over a twenty-year period across two countries.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>The thesis assesses existing explanations of strategy choice. It finds that political and legal opportunity approaches and resource-mobilisation explanations are unable to account for the case of legal mobilisation by the disability rights movement. Furthermore, the emphasis on these theoretical approaches has led to a neglect of other, potentially more important, variables influencing strategy-choice. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The&amp;nbsp;thesis offers a novel theoretical perspective focusing on shared and contested collective meaning frames within and across social movement organisations and an understanding of organisational ecology to better account for the overall development of disability rights legal mobilisation. Using a comparative process-tracing approach, it&amp;nbsp;teases out the sometimes subtle relationships between the evolution of the paradigm of disability, the transformation of relations between disability organisations, and variation in participation in strategic litigation across legal cases, groups and over time in the United Kingdom and Canada from 1985 to 2005. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The research is based on the public and archival records of these organisations (including annual reports, presentations to government, factums submitted to the courts and accounts in the media and secondary literature) as well as more than 60 interviews with disability rights activists, their allies and legal experts.&lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>70893</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>1700</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:description>Socio-Legal Studies Association Small Grants</gtr:description><gtr:end>2014-09-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>Socio-Legal Studies Association</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>D1B21FB3-A800-4611-BA63-78F0C4D2ABB5</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5453d2703d62e5.39019889</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2013-05-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput></gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This research explored the way in which disability activists in the United Kingdom and Canada have transformed their aspirations into legal claims in their quest for equality. It unpacked shifting conceptualizations of the political identity of disability and the role of a rights discourse in these dynamics. In doing so, it delves into the diffusion of disability rights among grassroots organizations and the traditional disability charities. The project drew on a wealth of primary sources including court records and campaign documents and encompassing interviews with more than sixty activists and legal experts. While showing that the disability rights movement has had a significant impact on equality jurisprudence in two countries, the findings also demonstrates that the act of mobilizing rights can have consequences, both intended and unintended, for social movements themselves.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The empirical findings can be expanded upon by studying other countries or social movement groups. The theoretical findings can be tested by examining other substantive policy areas.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>EBD59554-8A0A-4B14-A689-0EC3E4E8A89F</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56c098d7048c39.94921085</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Communities and Social Services/Policy,Healthcare,Government, Democracy and Justice</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>825F10FD-81A1-43A7-AD23-A95A94D06BBD</gtr:id><gtr:title>The Diffusion of Disability Rights in Europe</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Human Rights Quarterly</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/baf7ed09e9eb9b10c9df1e3e90db3295"><gtr:id>baf7ed09e9eb9b10c9df1e3e90db3295</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Vanhala, L</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:outcomeId>5453e1cb883f99.17872386</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>EA05AED4-4FAC-47B1-B939-38C11D9FA2DA</gtr:id><gtr:title>Making Rights a Reality?: Disability Rights Activists and Legal Mobilization</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http